5:
Whoa, look at the time.
I bet everyone's already asleep.
25:
Phew, Falsche...
What are you doing up so late?
30:
I'm organizing these items.
I found from corpses.
33: Oof, kind of sorry I asked...
35: Ah, but that's your job, isn't it, Falsche?
37:
Yes, I retrieve items from fallen
Kaleidoscope explorers.
And give them to their next of kin.
40: Forgive me. If you find it unnerving.
44:
Uh, no—heh—I mean it IS weird,
but now I've gotten used to it.
47:
After all, I've made a dead friend
myself, haven't I?
55: Not at all! He's a pretty nice guy!
59:
Anyway, there's a lot of stuff here.
Is your job done once you find all of the
rightful owners?
63:
I'm afraid not. I need to inform the
next of kin. About the deaths of their
loved ones.
70:
This dagger. For example. Belonged to
a woman who died saving her
companions.
72:
She saw her friends running away.
To safety. She felt relieved. Though
she was dying.
75:
Does that mean you can hear the
voices of the dead?
78:
No. Not exactly. I can only sense their
final emotions.
81:
People have many feelings. Some are
hard to put into words. Some are painful
to express.
83:
But their stories must be told.
Regardless.
91:
Considerate? Perhaps. I only do.
What comes naturally.
94: Sure, it's a great ability you have.
97:
But you're using it to carry out a super
important job. I don't think many people
would be that kind.
103:
It's rare for people to praise me. Usually.
They run away.
107:
But you value this work, right? Why else
would you rescue mementos from
unfortunate adventurers?
116: I take pride in my work. A lot of pride.
